Pages = {{59-69}},
Month = {{FEB}},
Abstract = {{Fear extinction can be defined as the weakening of the expression of a
   conditioned response (CR) by extended experience of nonreinforcement.
   Conceptually, two distinct models have been invoked to account for
   extinction. R. A. Rescorla and A. R. Wagner (1972, A theory of Pavlovian
   conditioning: Variations in the effectiveness of reinforcement and
   nonreinforcement, in A. H. B. W. F. Prokasy (Ed.), Classical
   conditioning: II. Current research and theory, pp. 64-99, New York, NY,
   Appleton-Century-Crofts) postulated that the number of exposure trials
   is the primary determinant of CR decrement, whereas C. R. Gallistel and
   J. Gibbon (2000, Time, rate, and conditioning, Psychological Review,
   Vol. 107, pp. 289-344) proposed that the decisive event is the cumulated
   exposure time to the nonreinforced conditioned stimulus (CS) elapsed
   after the last CS reinforcement. We evaluated these two accounts in a
   human differential fear conditioning study in which CR was measured with
   the fear-potentiated startle response. Cumulated duration of
   nonreinforcement falls to explain our findings, whereas the number of
   trials appeared critical. In fact, many CS trials with a duration
   shorter than the acquisition CS duration facilitated within-session
   extinction, but this effect did not predict the recovery of fear.}},
